{"title_page": "Windows-1252", "text_new": "{{Short description|Code page used for the Latin alphabets of Western European languages}}\n{{About|the character encoding commonly mislabeled as \"ANSI\"|the actual ANSI character encoding|ASCII|the actual \"ANSI extended Latin\" encoding|ANSEL}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox character encoding\n| name     = Windows-1252\n| mime     = windows-1252\n| image    = Windows-1252-infobox.svg\n| caption  = \n| alias    = \n| by       = [[Microsoft]]\n| standard = WHATWG Encoding Standard\n| lang     = [[English language|English]], [[Western Latin character sets (computing)|various others]]\n| status   =\n| extends  = [[ISO 8859-1]] (excluding C1 controls)\n| prev     = \n| next     = \n| encodes  = [[ISO 8859-15]]\n| classification = [[extended ASCII]], [[Windows-125x]]\n}}\n\n'''Windows-1252''' or '''CP-1252''' ([[code page]] 1252) is a single-byte [[character encoding]] of the [[Latin alphabet]], used by default in the [[legacy system|legacy]] components of [[Microsoft Windows]] for English and some other Western languages (other languages use different default encodings).\n\n{{As of|2020|04}}, 0.4% of all web sites declared use of Windows-1252,<ref name=\"encoding\">{{cite web|url=https://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/character_encoding|title=Historical trends in the usage of character encodings, April 2020|publisher=|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://w3techs.com/faq|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=}}</ref> but at the same time 2.2% used [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|ISO&nbsp;8859-1]] (0.7% of top-1000 websites),<ref name=\"encoding\"/> which by HTML5 standards should be considered the same encoding,<ref name=\"WHATWG\" /> so that 2.6% of web sites effectively use Windows-1252.\n\n==Details==\nThis character encoding is a [[superset]] of [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|ISO&nbsp;8859-1]] in terms of printable characters, but differs from the IANA's ISO-8859-1 by using displayable characters rather than control characters in the 80 to 9F ([[hexadecimal|hex]]) range. Notable additional characters include [[quotation mark|curly quotation marks]] and all the printable characters that are in [[ISO/IEC 8859-15|ISO&nbsp;8859-15]] (at different places than ISO&nbsp;8859-15). It is known to Windows by the [[Windows code page|code page]] number 1252, and by the [[Internet Assigned Numbers Authority|IANA]]-approved name \"windows-1252\".\n\n<!-- I think the following text is right but I need to do some checking first before I uncomment it (not quite true, yes it happened, but Netscape, Mosaic, et al. were at fault as well :)\nAt one stage many MS internet products produced text in Windows-1252 but marked as ISO-8859-1. This has resulted in other internet applications treating ISO-8859-1 as meaning Windows-1252 to maintain compatibility with Microsoft products.\nFollowing text is copied (mostly) from ISO-8859-1 page.\n-->It is very common to mislabel Windows-1252 text with the charset label ISO-8859-1. A common result was that all the quotes and apostrophes (produced by \"smart quotes\" in word-processing software) were replaced with question marks or boxes on non-Windows operating systems, making text difficult to read. Most modern web browsers and e-mail clients treat the [[media type]] charset ISO-8859-1 as Windows-1252 to accommodate such mislabeling. This is now standard behavior in the [[HTML5 in mobile devices|HTML5]] specification, which requires that documents advertised as ISO-8859-1 actually be parsed with the Windows-1252 encoding.<ref name=\"WHATWG\">{{cite web |url=https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/#names-and-labels |title=Encoding |at=sec. 5.2 Names and labels |publisher=[[WHATWG]] |date=27 January 2015 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204174315/https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/#names-and-labels |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><!-- No authors listed on page, but GitHub lists contributors as -->\n\nHistorically, the phrase \"ANSI Code Page\" was used in Windows to refer to non-DOS encodings; the intention was that most of these would be [[ANSI]] standards such as [[ISO-8859-1]]. Even though Windows-1252 was the first and by far most popular code page named so in Microsoft Windows parlance, the code page has never been an ANSI standard. Microsoft explains, \"The term ANSI as used to signify Windows code pages is a historical reference, but is nowadays a misnomer that continues to persist in the Windows community.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://download.microsoft.com/download/5/6/8/56803da0-e4a0-4796-a62c-ca920b73bb17/21-Unicode_WinXP.pdf |title=Unicode and Windows XP |page=1 |last1=Wissink |first1=Cathy |publisher=[[Microsoft]] |date=5 April 2002 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204175931/http://download.microsoft.com/download/5/6/8/56803da0-e4a0-4796-a62c-ca920b73bb17/21-Unicode_WinXP.pdf |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[LaTeX]] packages, CP-1252 is referred to as \"ansinew\".\n\n{{anchor|Code page layout}}\n\n==Character set==\nThe following table shows Windows-1252. Each character is shown with its [[Unicode]] equivalent based on the Unicode.org mapping of Windows-1252 with \"best fit\".<ref name=bestfit>{{cite web |url=https://www.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MICSFT/WindowsBestFit/bestfit1252.txt |title=Unicode mappings of Windows-1252 with 'Best Fit' |publisher=[[Unicode]] |accessdate=4 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204175922/http://www.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MICSFT/WindowsBestFit/bestfit1252.txt |archivedate=4 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| {{chset-tableformat}}\n{{chset-table-header|Windows-1252 (CP1252)}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|0_<br/>0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0000|[[Null character|NUL]]|0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0001|[[Start of heading|SOH]]|1}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl3|0002|[[St